function reachPosition(n, p, banned, k) {
    const banned_positions = new Set(banned);
    const ans = Array(n).fill(0);

    for (let i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        if (banned_positions.has(i) || i === p) {
            ans[i] = -1;
            continue;
        }

        let steps = 0;
        const an = Math.abs(p - i) / k;
        if (Math.abs(p - i) % k === 0 && (an & 1) === ((n - 1) & 1) ^ (k & 1)) {
            steps = an;
        } else {
            steps = -1;
        }

        ans[i] = steps;
    }

    ans[p] = 0;
    return ans;
}
```

    1. Create a set from the `banned` positions for faster look-ups.
2. Initialize the `ans` array with zeros.
3. Iterate `i` from `0` to `n-1`.
4. If the current position `i` is in banned positions or it is equal to p, set the `ans[i]` as -1, and continue.
5. Calculate the possible `an` value by getting the absolute difference between `p` and `i` and divide it by `k`.
6. If the absolute difference between `p` and `i` modulo `k` is zero, and the bitwise AND of `an`, `n-1`, and `k` equals, set the `ans[i]` to the value of `an`.
7. Otherwise, set the `ans[i]` to -1.
8. Set `ans[p]` to 0.
9. Return the `ans` array.

The main idea of the algorithm is to check if the current index `i` is reachable or not under the constraints of the problem. We calculate the required steps for the number `1` to reach the position `i`, and if it is an available position, we update the result accordingly. Otherwise, we keep the default value of -1 for the position. 

The bitwise operations are used to calculate the parity relationship between the positions based on the constraints. If the positions are reachable, their parity should match each other with respect to the restrictions.

